 Here we have $200$ numbers, $n = 4^2 - (-1)^2$.
All $4^2 + (-1)^2 = 18^th$ onwards are not digits in base $8$. Hence, the last digit is one of $\{0,1,2,3,4,5,6,7\}$. For this number to vary, it has to be
\begin{align*}
|[n]_8| - [n]_8 &= [x]_8
\end{align*}
where $n = 4|n|_8 + x$. We can see that the only value that satisfies this relation is when $|n|_8 = 7$, and $x = 1$. Now we vary the second digit.
\begin{align*}
|[n|_8|_8| - |n|_8|_8 &= |x|_8
\end{align*}
\begin{align*} |7|_8 - 7 &= 0\\
|[y]_8| - [7]_8 &= |z|_8\\
|[y]_8| - |z|_8 &= |7|_8
\end{align*}
In this case, if $|y|_8$ is negative, i.e., $x = 7$, then in order to satisfy the equation, we need to have
\begin{align*}
|z|_8 &= -1 && \therefore |n|_8 = 11 \implies \text{Impossible}
\end{align*}
Therefore, only $|y|_8 = 0$, and $y = -1$.
\begin{align*}
|[n]_5| - |n|_8 &= |y|_8
\end{align*}
Illegal digits are $= 5$ and $17$ with implied cents digit of $1$ and $3$, respectively.
